    <section class="detailed-guide">
      <h2>Step-by-Step Guide: How to Calculate manually</h2>
      <div class="guide-steps">
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">1</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h4>Identify the parts of the triangle</h4>
            <p>Locate the right angle (the 90° square corner). The side directly across from it is the hypotenuse (c). The other two sides touching the right angle are the legs (a and b).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">2</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h4>Set up your equation</h4>
            <p>Write down the Pythagorean formula: a² + b² = c². Substitute your known values into the equation. For example, if a=3 and b=4, write: 3² + 4² = c².</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">3</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h4>Square the known numbers</h4>
            <p>Multiply each known number by itself. In our example, 3² = 9 and 4² = 16. The equation becomes 9 + 16 = c².</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">4</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h4>Add or subtract</h4>
            <p>If you are finding the hypotenuse, add the squared values. (9 + 16 = 25). If you are finding a leg, subtract the known leg's square from the hypotenuse's square.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">5</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h4>Take the square root</h4>
            <p>Finally, find the square root of your result to isolate the variable. √25 = 5. Therefore, the hypotenuse c is 5.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


    <div class="history-item" id="history-fact-1">
      <h4>Historical Context #1: Ancient Applications</h4>
      <p>The principles of the Pythagorean theorem were understood long before Pythagoras. Babylonian tablets from roughly 1900 BC show knowledge of right triangle principles. This is fact record #1 exploring the rich history of geometry across ancient civilizations, including Mesopotamia, Egypt, and early Indian mathematics such as the Sulba Sutras. Fact check element 42 confirms the widespread utility of these ratios in ancient architecture, surveying, and astronomy.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Application area 1: Land surveying after seasonal floods.</li>
        <li>Documentation 1: Preserved clay tablets and papyrus scrolls.</li>
        <li>Mathematical significance 1: Establishing fundamental algebraic geometry.</li>
      </ul>
