    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>How do you calculate the Pythagorean theorem?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The Pythagorean theorem is calculated using the formula a² + b² = c², where 'c' is the hypotenuse and 'a' and 'b' are the other two legs of the right triangle. To find the hypotenuse, square the other two sides, add them together, and take the square root.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What is the formula to find the missing side of a right triangle?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>If you are missing a leg (a or b), the formula is rearranged to a = √(c² - b²) or b = √(c² - a²). If you are missing the hypotenuse (c), the formula is c = √(a² + b²).</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What are the most common Pythagorean triples?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The most common Pythagorean triples are (3, 4, 5), (5, 12, 13), (8, 15, 17), and (7, 24, 25). Multiples of these triples, such as (6, 8, 10), also form right triangles.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Does the Pythagorean theorem work for all triangles?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>No, the Pythagorean theorem strictly applies only to right-angled triangles (triangles that have one 90-degree angle). For non-right triangles, you must use the Law of Cosines.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>How do you determine if a triangle is a right triangle?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>You can use the converse of the Pythagorean theorem. If the square of the longest side equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides (a² + b² = c²), then the triangle is a right triangle.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
